        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">CD refers to the <ref target="./DCP-LETT-2299.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from J. D. Hooker and Charles Lyell to the Linnean Society, 30 June 1858</ref>, which was printed as an introduction to the contributions by CD and <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_4935.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Alfred Russel Wallace</ref> (Darwin and Wallace 1858).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">For CD’s alterations, see <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1581.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Correspondence</hi></ref> vol.7, Appendix III.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-2307.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from J. D. Hooker, 13–15 July 1858</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f4"><ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_565.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Bentham 1858</ref>. <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_398.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">George Bentham</ref> was an expert on temperate and tropical plants and had not previously studied the British flora. CD and Hooker considered Bentham to be a far better botanist than <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_214.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Charles Cardale Babington</ref>.</note>
